The paper deals with the construction and analysis of low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes, which are commonly studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and coding theory (cs.DM) communities. The paper also makes use of graph theory concepts, such as cages and trapping sets, which are relevant to computer science (cs.CC) and network science (cs.NI). Finally, the paper's focus on deriving upper bounds on the minimum distance of LDPC codes suggests a potential application in signal processing (cs.SI).
